about:
Impacting the world positively, one way or another. This is what I strive for.

In high school I got passionate about mathematics and physics and how they could help understand the Physical World around us, the ‚Äúhardware‚Äù. This led me to study building structures. But then, while I joined the family business and started working in the ‚Äúreal word‚Äù I realized the importance of understanding and managing the Human World around us, the ‚Äúsoftware‚Äù.

My philosophies are: Define a purpose. Build a great team. Inspire the team to win. Find the right questions to ask. And the rest follows (strategy definition, execution, etc.).

After I joined the family business, in concrete manufacturing (PREFAB), I realized the importance of management and leadership, on top of engineering. I then had to learn how to solve problems in a family-run manufacturing business, saving the company from bankruptcy.

I could advise private and public organizations from within an international development agency (IFC of the World Bank). I helped turn around a public organization (OFPPT Corporate Services) fixing an incentive-based training scheme for SMEs (not for profit) and laying down a strategy for selling training to SMEs (for-profit).

Then I joined a totally new industry for me, in agriculture, where I am thrilled to have inspired a team to make a company a world leader in some areas of our industry and triple revenues and profits in 9 years.

After almost 20 years of work experience in various sectors, and looking ahead, I became passionate about thinking out of the box to reinvent businesses. It is the only possible way for companies to continue to exist and thrive in these turbulent times.

My subjects of interest: vision (re)definition, corporate strategy, marketing strategy, organizational design, execution and technology integration.

Always open to challenges, feel free to get in touch and discuss: jalal.charaf@gmail.com | +212 6 69 58 44 07.

about:
Research-driven professional with over a decade of experience at the intersection of artificial intelligence, autonomous systems, and cybersecurity. Alternators then play this role. This results in limiting the amount of energy obtained by wind farms to 20% of the total power in an electric grid, in order to ensure power regulation and grid stability. In this project, we present a possible solution to this problem, based on modeling a control strategy of a variable speed wind turbine. about:
I am currently a PhD researcher in Management Sciences, focusing on the use of artificial intelligence to model entrepreneurial failure within business ecosystems. My research aims to explore how personal factors related to the entrepreneur‚Äîsuch as lack of skills, stress, and decision-making errors‚Äîinteract with the entrepreneurial ecosystem to either mitigate or exacerbate business failure. My approach is rooted in a positivist research paradigm and involves a rigorous methodology, including a systematic literature review, a conceptual model, and later, the application of AI-based techniques for analysis and prediction.

Prior to my PhD, I earned a Master‚Äôs degree in Financial and Accounting Management, where I specialized in customer risk analysis and broader financial and operational risk management. This academic foundation provided me with strong analytical skills and a deep understanding of risk assessment in organizational contexts.

To support my research and applied projects, I pursued certifications from Google and IBM in Data Analysis, Advanced Data Analysis, Project Management, AI Engineering, and Data Science. I have since developed hands-on experience in Python programming, machine learning, deep learning, computer vision, NLP, as well as DevOps tools like Docker, Git, and CI/CD pipelines. My work also includes academic writing using LaTeX, bibliometric and systematic reviews, and the development of conceptual and theoretical frameworks for research in entrepreneurship.

projects:
[{'name': 'Climate Risk Modeling', 'description': 'As a dedicated professional in the field of climate risk modeling, I specialize in leveraging advanced methodologies to assess and mitigate the impacts of climate change. My work involves integrating a variety of modeling techniques, including Integrated Assessment Models (IAMs), machine learning algorithms, and insurance models, to accurately estimate climatic risks, particularly in the context of Morocco.

Integrated Assessment Models (IAMs) provide a comprehensive framework for analyzing the complex interactions between socioeconomic factors and climate systems. By utilizing IAMs, I can assess the long-term consequences of different climate policies and adaptation strategies, enabling informed decision-making at both regional and national levels.

Machine learning models offer valuable insights by analyzing vast amounts of data to identify patterns and trends in climatic variables. By applying machine learning algorithms to historical climate data, I can develop predictive models to anticipate future climate scenarios and associated risks in Morocco.

Insurance models play a crucial role in quantifying and managing climate risks by providing financial protection against adverse climate events. By collaborating with insurance companies and leveraging their expertise in risk assessment and management, I can enhance our understanding of climate-related vulnerabilities and develop innovative insurance solutions tailored to the Moroccan context.

Through my interdisciplinary approach in climate risk modeling, I am committed to supporting stakeholders in Morocco in building resilience to climate change and safeguarding their communities, economies, and ecosystems for future generations.'}]

about:

I am a professor at the Hassan II Institute of Agronomy and Veterinary Medicine. I advised 60 MS students and eight PhD students.  I have published several papers on natural resources, especially on digital soil mapping, soil and water conservation in the context of global change, remote sensing and geographic information systems.

I was a Chief of Party of an Agricultural Systems Modeling project. I was the Coordinator of PRAD project on soil vulnerability to erosion. I am the Coordinator of the doctoral Research program on Soil and Water Conservation. I was a Member of the scientific advisory committee of MCA project ‚Äì Morocco. I was a Member of the working group on soil fertility map of Morocco. I was the coordinator of the research team on soil and water conservation project funded by MCC. I am a member of the organizing and scientific committee of the conference "Vulnerability of the Mediterranean soils to water erosion: state of knowledge and adaptation strategies in the face of global change" (http://www.soil-vulnerability-rabat2018.ma/En/). I am the President of the Hiking Atlas Club of IAV Hassan II and the Secretary General of the Club El Harka.

I am a member of the International Soil Conservation Organization, a member of the Student Initiative for Free Enterprise, a member of the World Association of Soil and Water Conservation, a member of the Moroccan Association of Soil Science, a member of the High Moulouya Association for the Protection of Environment Nature and Ecotourism.
projects: [{'name': 'Mediterranean Agricultural Soils Conservation Under Global Change (MASCC)', 'description': 'MASCC project aims to address mitigation and adaptation strategies to global change by assessing current and future development of Mediterranean agricultural soil vulnerability to erosion in relation to projected land use, agricultural practices and climate change. It targets to i) assess the similarities/dissimilarities in dominant factors affecting the current Mediterranean agricultural soil vulnerability by exploring a wide range of Mediterranean contexts; ii) improve the ability to evaluate the impact of extreme events on both the current and projected agricultural soil vulnerability and sediment delivery at the catchment outlet; iii) evaluate the vulnerability and resilience of agricultural production to a combination of potential changes in a wide range of Mediterranean contexts and iv) provide guidelines on sustainable agricultural conservation strategies adapted to each agro-ecosystem and taking into consideration both on- and off-site erosion effects and socio-economics issues.'}, {'name': ' Adaptation des mosa√Øques paysag√®res dans les agrosyst√®mes pluviaux m√©diterran√©es pour une gestion durable de la production agricole, des ressources en eau et en sol.', 'description': 'Mediterranean Rainfed Agrosystems (MRAs) provide various environmental and economic services of importance such as food production, preservation of employment and local know how, downstream water delivery or mitigation of rural exodus.These services have progression margins, thus making investments in such agrosystems highly profitable. In the meantime, expected climate change combined with demography and market pressures threaten MRA future abilities to satisfy the aforementioned services. In the context of mitigating the pressures induced by global change, ALMIRA aims to explore the modulation of landscape mosaics within MRAs to optimize landscape services. Following recommendations from think-tank IAASTD (2008), significant advances are expected by reasoning spatial organizations of land uses and cropping systems.'}]

projects:
[{'name': "MASTER'S THESIS PROJECT: Implementation of a Big Data and Data Science Solution for Designing a Next Best Offer Recommendation System", 'description': 'The main aim of my internship project is to assist the INWI operator in recommending the best offer to their customers among various options. This will boost the business value of their "NBO" Use Case, and it will also let me include an entirely new perspective to the preceding Use Case.
In the first step, the study focused on the extraction, transformation, and loading (commonly called "data ingestion") of three data sources using the Cloudera Hadoop platform, as well as the Big Data tools, namely Hadoop and its ecosystem, in addition to  the Python language and the MySQL relational database.
The study's second phase involved examining the dataset, handling any missing data, creating visual representations, and selecting the most pertinent data for the research. On top of that, an agglomerative clustering model was performed on the dataset to extract the distinct cluster groups. Afterward, I used five supervised learning models to compare the results and obtain the best evaluation of the recommendation model. Finally, a function has been set up to offer each client three recommendation offers, based on the results of the best model.
To summarize, I proposed a new Scope for the existing Use Case, collected data from different sources, ingested the data into the Data Lake, proposed a star schema consisting of a fact table with new Kpis and 5 dimension tables, performed exploratory data analysis, data cleaning, management of imbalanced data, data transformation and feature engineering and ultimately developed 5 Machine Learning models to offer INWI's customers the next best offer, at the right time, achieving 85.54% accuracy for the XGBoost model.'}, {'name': "PFE Licence : Mise en place d'un site Web pour la gestion d'une Bibliotheque (Java/J2EE)", 'description': ''}]
